0011|- [HelpText]
0012|#SMOOTH <data>,<series>,<smoothened_series>,<width>
S   |        <    > <      > <                 > <     >
0013|*smooths <series> in <data> using a technique based on FFT
S   |         <      >    <    >
0014|*(Fast Fourier Transformation) with a window whose full width is of
0015|*order <width> neighboring points and saves the smoothened values as
S   |       <     >
0016|*<smoothened_series>.
S   | <                 >
0018|*SMOOTH can be used for smoothing any variable Y in relation to another
0019|*variable X by first sorting the data by X and then applying SMOOTH for
0020|*Y.
0021|*Numerical method:
0022|*SMOOTH removes any linear trend and uses then FFT to low-pass filter
0023|*the data. The linear trend is reinserted at the end.
0024|*<width> gives the "amount of smoothing", specified as the number of
S   | <     >
0025|*points over which the data should be smoothened (not necessarily an
0026|*integer). Zero gives no smoothing at all. The results of SMOOTH are
0027|*generally in accord with the notion "draw a smooth curve through these
0028|*scattered points".
0029|*Reference: "Numerical Recipes" (1987) by Press, Flannery, Teukolsky, and
0030|*                                                              Vetterling
